In the world of Hyprland (a dynamic tiling Wayland compositor), understanding the difference between tiling, floating, and scratchpads is the key to mastering your workflow.

Think of it as the difference between a perfectly organized bookshelf (tiling) and a desk covered in sticky notes (floating).

1. Floating Windows
By default, Hyprland is a tiling window manager, meaning it automatically sizes windows to fill the screen without overlapping. A floating window, however, ignores this grid.

Behavior: It behaves like a window in Windows or macOS—you can move it anywhere, resize it manually, and it can sit on top of other tiled windows.

Best for: Small utilities like calculators, file pickers, or media players that don't need to take up half your screen.

How to trigger: Usually, you use a keybind (often super + V or super + float) or define a "window rule" in your config to make specific apps always float.

2. The Scratchpad (Special Workspace)
In Hyprland, the "scratchpad" is technically called a Special Workspace. Think of it as a "hidden drawer" where you keep tools you use frequently but don't want cluttering your main view.

Behavior: When you "send" a window to the scratchpad, it disappears from your current view. When you "summon" the scratchpad, that window slides back into view over your current work.

The Benefit: You don't have to navigate through multiple workspaces to find your terminal or music player. It's just one keystroke away, regardless of which workspace you are currently on.

Use Case: Most users keep a terminal (like Kitty or Alacritty) or a system monitor (like BTOP) in the scratchpad.

Key Differences at a Glance
Feature	Tiled Window	Floating Window	Scratchpad (Special)
Position	Fixed in a grid	Anywhere on screen	Hidden until called
Sizing	Automatic	Manual	Can be tiled or floating
Focus	Part of the layout	"Always on top" feel	Context-independent
Pro-Tip: The "Drop-down" Terminal
Most Hyprland users combine these two concepts. They set a terminal to be floating and move it to the special workspace. This creates a "drop-down" terminal effect similar to Quake or Guake, where a small terminal pops up over your work and vanishes when you're done.

