That is a perfect use case for a scratchpad. Instead of manually navigating to your notes every time you get stuck, you can hit a key combination and have your "cheat sheet" instantly slide over your current work.

To make this work seamlessly, we’ll use a terminal-based text editor (like nano, vim, or nvim) to open that specific file.

The Plan
We need to tell Hyprland to:

Create a "Special Workspace" (the scratchpad).

Launch your terminal with the command to open your helpfile.txt.

Set a "Window Rule" so that this specific window is always floating and sized nicely.

The Configuration
Add these lines to your hyprland.conf. I've used kitty as the terminal example, but you can swap it for alacritty or foot.

Bash
# 1. Define the window rule for your help file
# This ensures it floats and stays a specific size
windowrule = float, ^(help_terminal)$
windowrule = size 800 500, ^(help_terminal)$
windowrule = center, ^(help_terminal)$

# 2. Bind a key to toggle the scratchpad (Super + H for Help)
bind = $mainMod, H, togglespecialworkspace, help

# 3. Launch the file in the special workspace on startup
# We give it a unique 'class' so the window rule above catches it
exec-once = [workspace special:help silent] kitty --class help_terminal nano ~/helpfile.txt
How this works:
--class help_terminal: This is the "secret sauce." By giving the terminal a unique name, we can tell Hyprland to float only this specific terminal without affecting your normal ones.

togglespecialworkspace, help: This command is a toggle. Pressing Super + H will bring the file up; pressing it again will hide it.

silent: This ensures that when you boot up your PC, the help file loads in the background without jumping in your face immediately.

A Quick Tip
If you prefer a GUI editor (like VS Code or Mousepad), you can do the same thing, but terminals are generally much faster for "drop-down" style scratchpads because they launch almost instantly.

