To make your help file look like a polished part of your UI, we can apply specific "decoration" rules. This allows you to read your notes without completely losing sight of the documentation or code behind them.

Add these lines to your hyprland.conf (under your existing window rules):

Bash
# Apply a slight transparency and a blur effect to the help terminal
windowrule = opacity 0.85 0.8, ^(help_terminal)$
windowrule = blur, ^(help_terminal)$

# Optional: Add a distinct border color so you know it's your 'Special' window
windowrule = bordercolor rgb(EE82EE), ^(help_terminal)$
Why this is helpful:
Contextual Awareness: The opacity 0.85 (active) and 0.8 (inactive) lets you see the "shape" of the windows behind it, helping you remember exactly where you left off.

Readability: The blur rule ensures that even if the background is "busy" (like a website with lots of text), the text in your helpfile.txt remains sharp and readable.

Visual Cue: The bordercolor helps distinguish this "utility" window from your standard workspace terminals.

Pro-Tip: Making it "Sticky"
If you ever want your help file to stay visible even when you switch to a different workspace (Workspace 1 to Workspace 2), you can add a "pin" bind.

Add this to your bind section:
bind = $mainMod ALT, P, pin

Now, if you summon your help file and press Super + Alt + P, it will "stick" to your glass and follow you across every workspace until you unpin it or hide the scratchpad.

