To make your help file save automatically, the secret isn't actually in Hyprland—it's in the text editor you choose to run inside that terminal.

Since you're likely using a terminal-based editor for this scratchpad, here are the two best ways to ensure your notes are never lost.

Option 1: Use vim or nvim (Recommended)
Vim and Neovim have an "autowrite" feature. You can tell it to save the file every time the window loses focus or after a certain amount of time.

Modify your Hyprland config to launch the file with the autowrite command:

Bash
exec-once = [workspace special:help silent] kitty --class help_terminal nvim -c "set autowriteall" ~/helpfile.txt
Add a "Focus" trigger in your .vimrc or init.lua:
Adding this snippet to your editor's config will save the file the millisecond you toggle the scratchpad away (because the window loses focus):

Vim Script
" Save whenever focus is lost
au FocusLost * :wa
Option 2: Use micro (The Easiest Way)
If you aren't a Vim user, Micro is a fantastic modern terminal editor that feels like Windows Notepad (Ctrl+S to save, etc.) and has a built-in "autosave" option.

Install Micro: sudo pacman -S micro (or your distro's manager).

Update your Hyprland config:

Bash
exec-once = [workspace special:help silent] kitty --class help_terminal micro -autosave 1 ~/helpfile.txt
The -autosave 1 flag tells it to save every 1 second after a change is made.

Why "Auto-Save" is better than "Save on Close"
In a tiling window manager like Hyprland, we rarely "close" the scratchpad app; we usually just hide the workspace.

Hiding: The app is still running in the background. If your computer crashes or you logout, a "Save on Close" prompt will get stuck in the background and you might lose data.

Auto-Save: It writes to the disk while you type, so even if you kill the terminal process, your helpfile.txt is already updated.

Summary Table: Which one to choose?
Editor	Auto-Save Method	Difficulty
Micro	-autosave 1 flag	Very Easy
Vim / Nvim	set autowriteall	Medium (Requires config)
Nano	Manual (Ctrl+O)	Hard (No native auto-save)
